Russia debates its future.
JAROSLAWL: Russia, say many, lacks a "civil society."
But this is partially compensated by a quite interesting public space where serious issues are debated, and where fleeting glances at the powerful are not entirely limited to television clips.
In the first two weeks of September, there were consecutive meetings of two important Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The former took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sochi on the Black Sea.
The latter, in Yaroslavl, culminated in a symposium with President Dmitry Medvedev.
Scientists, members of think tanks, and journalists (both Russian and foreign) discussed Russia's future together with important politicians and business leaders.
Three things made these events something special in typically Russian fashion.
The first was the intense media interest.
Even an extremely camera-shy scientist could suddenly find themselves as a Russian TV star.
The second was the willingness of both Putin and Medvedev to publicly engage with experts on their own intellectual turf.
I can only think of one Western political leader from recent times who had the confidence to do this; that was Bill Clinton.
And finally, the two events marked the emergence of two rival political forums, each exuding the faint but unmistakable scent of an impending conflict.
For those with eyes to see, these two conferences offered a fascinating insight into a crumbling diarchy.
The main topic of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography condemned it to authoritarian rule.
If democracy belongs to the future, shouldn't Russia's fate be to miss out on it?
The pessimists—especially Russian historians—argued that it would be difficult, if not impossible, for Russia to overcome its autocratic legacy.
Lew Beloussow from Moscow's State Lomonosov University argued that autocracy in Russia, supported by the passivity and endurance of the Russians, repeatedly rises like a phoenix from the ashes.
The Bolsheviks had inherited the autocracy from the tsars; Putin has rediscovered the old monarchical principle of anointing his successor, thereby bypassing the democratic competition for the presidency.
Radicals like Vladimir Ryschkow rejected this historical determinism. According to Ryschkow, authoritarianism should not be legitimized by reference to history.
The protests are increasing.
It is the yoke of Putin, not that of history, that weighs heavily on Russia.
Much of this discussion lacked clarity, as is typically the case in such discussions.
Most participants were unable to distinguish between history as a limitation and history as a determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never fully overcome their history, but every history offers many different possibilities.
Countries are not genetically programmed like animals.
The discussion about autocracy was inevitably linked to other topics.
The autocracy in Russia has been defended as necessary for a world empire.
But this leads to another question: Does Russia need a world empire?
Can Russia renounce its imperial past and maintain normal relations with its recently independent neighbors such as Ukraine and Georgia?
Can it actually be a completely "normal" actor on the world stage?
At the conference in Yaroslavl with Medvedev, the focus shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
They all agreed that Russia must diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
As Medvedev emphasized, a raw materials-based economy is always vulnerable to fluctuations in raw material prices.
But roughly speaking, there are two views regarding the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy results from a modern economy, as a kind of reward for the hard work that has been done.
If the state promotes modernization from above, then democracy will grow naturally, albeit slowly, as a result of increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The Kremlin's chief ideologue, Vladimir Surkov, has suggested that a genuine democracy requires a "democracy in the mind," thereby implying that this desirable mental state is still far from being achieved in Russia.
The alternative viewpoint, held by people like Igor Jurgens, the head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the Russian state, in its current form, lacks any real incentive to reform its own poor economic habits—or those of the Russians.
The previous development confirms this.
Russia has experienced a modest recovery from the recession.
Yet there is almost no innovation; the elites are content to lead comfortable lives through revenues from the energy sector, and corruption continues unabated.
Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, lacking a mobilizing element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
There is a clear gap between Putin and Medvedev.
Medvedev is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must eventually come, but with Putin, the emphasis is clearly on the "later," whereas Medvedev has added a liberating voice to the public discourse in Russia.
Cynics claim this is merely a misleading routine following the motto "Good cop, bad cop."
But words matter, and a new rhetoric is a political force in its own right.
Medvedev's main strategic goal must now be to secure a second presidential term.
He cannot openly question Putin's legacy but must position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
It is a difficult balancing act, because Putin can reclaim the presidency at any time if he believes that his former protégé intends to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin has created.
Nineteen years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction remains as unclear as ever.
This is especially important for the Russians, but because Russia spans the vast Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity regarding Russia's future compels the rest of us to remain in a state of constant concern.
Is Russia part of the West?
Does his history and geography grant him an unmistakably Eurasian perspective capable of mediating a potential collision between Western and Eastern civilizations, or between Christianity and Islam?
Russia cannot be neatly categorized within geopolitical frameworks, but it remains too important to be ignored.
